{{IndicText}} '''Bhekasana''' ({{lang-sa|भेकासन}}; [[IAST]]: Bhekāsana),<ref name="Iyengar2000">{{cite book | title=Light on Yoga | publisher=Schocken | author=Iyengar, B.K.S | authorlink=B.K.S. Iyengar| year=1979 | location=New York | pages=126–8| isbn=0-8052-1031-8}}</ref> or '''Frog posture'''<ref name="YogaJ">{{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/practice/1390 | title = Yoga Journal&nbsp;– Frog posture | accessdate = 2012-12-07| deadurl= no}}</ref> is an [[asana]]. It is one of several poses that put the body in a shape like that of a frog: another is Mandukasana.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandukasana |url=https://www.yogapedia.com/definition/7244/mandukasana |publisher=Yogapedia |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>
==Etymology==
The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''Bheka'' (भेका, bheka) meaning "frog",<ref name="Iyengar2000"/> and ''asana'' (आसन) meaning "posture"<ref name="Sinha1996">{{cite book|last=Sinha|first=S.C.|title=Dictionary of Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zzRvh1fRzEC&pg=PA18|accessdate=9 April 2011|date=1 June 1996|publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD.|isbn=978-81-7041-293-9|page=18}}</ref> since the asana resembles a frog.
==Benefits and Risks== *Though prolonged practice can cure flat feet.<ref name="Iyengar2000"/><ref name="YogaJ"/> *Relieves pain in the heels due to [[calcaneal spur]]s and in knees due to [[gout]]<ref name="Iyengar2000"/> *Stretches ankles, thighs and groins, abdomen and chest, and throat, and deep hip flexors ([[Psoas major muscle|psoas]])<ref name="YogaJ"/> *Strengthens the back muscles<ref name="YogaJ"/> *Improves [[Human position|posture]]<ref name="YogaJ"/> *Stimulates the organs of the abdomen<ref name="YogaJ"/> *Awakens the [[Kundalini energy|kundalini]]<ref name="YogaJ"/>
