{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox Mandir | name = Dharmrajeshwar | image = Dharmrajeshwar.JPG | alt = | caption = | map_type = India#India Madhya Pradesh | map_caption = Location in Madhya Pradesh | coordinates = {{coord|24|11|38.22|N|75|29|56.42|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}} | other_names = | country = [[India]] | state = [[Madhya Pradesh]] | district = [[Mandsaur District|Mandsaur]] | location = [[Garoth]] tehsil | elevation_m = | deity = | festivals= | architecture = [[Indian rock-cut architecture]] | temple_quantity = | monument_quantity= | inscriptions = | year_completed = 4th - 5th century | creator = | website = }}
'''Dharmrajeshwar''' is an ancient [[Buddhist]] and [[Hindu]] [[cave]] temple site of 4th-5th century in [[Mandsaur]] district in [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]. It is an example of [[Indian rock-cut architecture]], situated in [[Garoth]] tahsil of [[Mandsaur]] district at a distance of 4&nbsp;km from [[Chandwasa]] town and 106&nbsp;km from [[Mandsaur]] city. Nearest railway station is [[Shamgarh]] about 22&nbsp;km. Its original name is [[Dhamnār]] (धमनार).<ref>Usha Agarwal:Mandsaur Zile Ke Puratatvik samarakon ki paryatan ki drishti se sansadhaniyata - Ek Adhyayan, Chirag Prakashan Udaipur, 2007, p. 27</ref>
==Dharmarajeshwara temple== It has the 9th century [[monolith]]ic temple of Dharmarajeshwara, carving it out of solid natural rock. The temple is carved out of a rock of size 50 metre in length, 20 metre in width and 9 metre deep. It has a sanctum with a ''Sabhamandapa'' and porch. The spire of the shrine is in the north Indian style. The architecture of Dharmarajesvara temple can be compared with [[Ellora Kailasanathar Temple|Kailash Temple]] of [[Ellora]]. There is a big temple in the middle 14.53 metre in length and 10 metre in width. Around the main temple there are seven small temples. There is a big [[Shivalinga]] in the main temple along with a statue of [[Vishnu]]. Engraved on the entrance gate are figures of Vishnu and [[Lakshami]]. There are statues of [[Bhairava]], [[Kali]], [[Shiva]], [[Garuda]] and [[Parvati]]. The temple seems to be devoted to both [[Shiva]] and Vishnu.<ref>Usha Agarwal:Mandsaur Zile Ke Puratatvik samarakon ki paryatan ki drishti se sansadhaniyata - Ek Adhyayan, Chirag Prakashan Udaipur, 2007, p. 28</ref>
==Caves== {{Main|Dhamnar Caves}} There a caves and temples cut into the coarse laterite rock of the southern hill. There is a series of fourteen the 7th century rock-cut [[Buddhist]] [[caves]] with monasteries and Stupas, cut in a hill called [[Chandanagiri]].
==See also== [[Indian rock-cut architecture]]
