{{Hinduism by country}} The history of '''Hinduism in Madagascar''' began with the arrival of primarily [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] from the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] region of [[India]] as far back as 1870, at which time [[Madagascar]] was a [[French colony]] known as Malagache. These were predominantly [[Muslim]] ([[Khoja]]s, [[Ismaili]]s and Daoudi [[Dawoodi Bohra|Bohras]]), but a small number were [[Hindu]]s.<ref name="id">[http://indiandiaspora.nic.in/diasporapdf/chapter8.pdf NRI<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206063957/http://indiandiaspora.nic.in/diasporapdf/chapter8.pdf |date=2012-02-06 }}</ref>
==Current status== The International Religious Freedom Report 2006 reported that there is a small Hindu presence in Madagascar.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71310.htm "International Religious Freedom Report 2006"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/64rJD9LRN?url=http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71310.htm |date=2012-01-21 }} at the U.S. Department of State</ref> Many of them are business owners, or IT professionals who have lived in the country for generations. The majority speak [[Hindi]] or [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], although some other Indian languages are spoken. Nowadays, younger generations speak at least three languages, including [[French language|French]] or [[English language|English]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Malagasy language|Malagasy]].
