{{italic title}} {{taxobox |name = ''Leonurus cardiaca'' |image = Motherwort.jpg |regnum = [[Plantae]] |unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]] |unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]] |unranked_ordo = [[Asterids]] |ordo = [[Lamiales]] |familia = [[Lamiaceae]] |genus = ''[[Leonurus]]'' |species = '''''L. cardiaca''''' |binomial = ''Leonurus cardiaca'' |binomial_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Linnæus|first1=Carolus|title=Species Plantarum|date=1753|publisher=Laurentius Salvius|location=Holmia|page=584|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358605|volume=2}}</ref> }} '''''Leonurus cardiaca''''', known as '''motherwort''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web|title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |accessdate=2014-10-17 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> is an [[Herbaceous plant|herbaceous]] [[perennial plant]] in the mint family, [[Lamiaceae]]. Other common names include '''throw-wort''', '''lion's ear''', and '''lion's tail'''. Lion's tail also being a common name for ''[[Leonotis leonurus]]'', and lion's ear, a common name for ''[[Leonotis nepetifolia]]''. Originally from [[Central Asia]] and southeastern Europe, it is now found worldwide, spread largely due to its use as a [[herbalism|herbal remedy]].
==Description== ''Leonurus cardiaca'' has a squarish stem which is clad in short hairs and is often purplish, especially near the nodes. The [[opposite leaves]] have serrated margins and are palmately lobed with long [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]]; basal leaves are wedge shaped with three points while the upper leaves have five. They are slightly hairy above and greyish beneath. Flowers appear in leaf axils on the upper part of the plant and have three-lobed bracts. The [[Calyx (botany)|calyx]] of each flower is bell-shaped and has five lobes. The [[corolla (flower)|corolla]] is irregular, {{convert|8|to|12|mm|1|abbr=on}} long, fused, long-tubed with two lips. The upper lip is convex and covered with white hairs and the lower lip is three-lobed and downward-curving and spotted with red. The flowers are pink to lilac in colour often with furry lower lips. There are four stamens, two short and two longer, and the fruit is a four-chambered [[schizocarp]]. The plant grows to about {{convert|60|to|100|cm|0|abbr=on}} in height and blooms during July and August.<ref name=NatureGate>{{cite web |url=http://www.luontoportti.com/suomi/en/kukkakasvit/motherwort |title=Motherwort: ''Leonurus cardiaca'' |publisher=NatureGate |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>
==Distribution and habitat== Motherwort is probably native to the southeastern part of Europe and central Asia where it has been cultivated since ancient times. Its natural habitat is beside roadsides, in vacant fields, waste ground, rubbish dumps and other disturbed areas. This plant prefers well drained soil and a partly shady location. Introduced to North America as a [[Forage (honey bee)|bee foraging plant]] and to attract [[bumble bee]]s, this perennial herb is now considered [[invasive species|invasive]]. It is hardy in [http://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/ USDA climate zones] 4–8.<ref>[http://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=LECA2 Leonurus cardiaca L. Common motherwort.] NRCS PLANTS database. Retrieved 26 February 2016.</ref>
==Chemistry== [[File:Stachydrine.svg|thumb|200px|Chemical structure of stachydrine]] The herb contains the [[alkaloid]] [[leonurine]].<ref name="herbal_therapy_supplements">{{Cite book | last1 = Kuhn | first1 = Merrily A. | last2 = Winston | first2 = David | last3 = Marderosian, Ara Harold | first3 = Der | title = Herbal therapy supplements: a scientific traditional approach | year = 2000 | publisher = Lippincott | location = Philadelphia | isbn = 978-0-7817-2643-6 | pages = 232 }}</ref> Among other chemical constituents, it also contains [[stachydrine]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 23923634 | year = 2013 | author1 = Kuchta | first1 = K | title = Stachydrine in Leonurus cardiaca, Leonurus japonicus, Leonotis leonurus: Detection and quantification by instrumental HPTLC and 1H-qNMR analyses | journal = Die Pharmazie | volume = 68 | issue = 7 | pages = 534–40 | last2 = Volk | first2 = R. B. | last3 = Rauwald | first3 = H. W. }}</ref> bitter [[iridoid]] [[glycoside]]s ([[leonuride]]), [[diterpinoid]]s, [[flavonoid]]s (including [[rutin]] and [[quercetin]]), [[tannin]]s, volatile oils, and [[vitamin A]].
