{{Orisa-Ifá sidebar| Variants}}
'''Trinidad Orisha''', also known as '''Shango''', is a [[syncretic religion]] in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] and is of [[Caribbean]] origin, originally from West Africa ([[Yoruba religion]])  and influenced by [[Roman Catholicism]]. Trinidad Orisha incorporates elements of [[Spiritual Baptist|Spiritual Baptism]], and the closeness between Orisha and Spiritual Baptism has led to use of the term "Shango Baptist" to refer to members of either or both religions. Anthropologist James Houk described Trinidad Orisha as an "[[Afro-American religion|Afro-American religious complex]]",<ref>{{cite book|last=Houk|first=James|title=Spirits, Blood, and Drums: The Orisha Religion in Trinidad|year=1995|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia, PA}}</ref> incorporating elements mainly of [[traditional African religion]] and [[Yoruba religion|Yoruba]] and incorporates some elements of [[Christianity]] ([[Catholicism]] and [[Protestantism]]), [[Hinduism]], [[Islam]] (especially [[Sufism]]), [[Buddhism]],  [[Judaism]], [[Bahá'í]], and Trinidad [[Kabbalah]].

==Ritual music==
{{See also|List of Caribbean membranophones}}
Trinidad Orisha practice involves [[Call and response (music)|call and response]] singing accompanied by a trio of drums. Orisha drums are double-headed bi-tensorial cylinders derived from Yoruba ''bembe'' drums (similar to the Cuban ''Iyesá'' drums). The drum that is lowest in pitch is called the ''bo'' or ''kongo''. The lead drum is called "center drum," "big drum," or ''bembe''. The smallest drum, highest in pitch, is called ''umele''. The first two drums are played with a single stick plus hand combination, while the ''umele'' is played with a pair of sticks. All of the sticks are curved at the end, and resemble a shepherd's crook.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bazinet|first=Ryan|title=Re-Constructing Place and Space|year=2012|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|editor=Kamille Gentles-Peart and Maurice L. Hall|chapter=Shango Dances Across the Water: Music and the Re-Construction of Trinidadian Orisha in New York City}}</ref> The language of the songs has been referred to as "Trinidad Yoruba"<ref>{{cite book|last=Warner-Lewis|first=Maureen|title=Trinidad Yoruba: From Mother Tongue to Memory|year=1996|publisher=University of Alabama Press|location=Tuscaloosa}}</ref> and is derived from the [[Yoruba language]].

